    <h1>Typological Grounding</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      The same grounding question, where typology supplies the ground truth.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is an early direction, still taking shape — not a settled thesis line. It carries the
      question that runs through the rest of my work — <em>is a model's behaviour licensed by the
      genuine structure, or by a surface proxy that correlates with it?</em> — into a domain where
      the structure itself varies from language to language.
    </p>

    <h2>The idea</h2>
    <p>
      Languages split the work of encoding meaning across <strong>morphology</strong>,
      <strong>word order</strong>, and <strong>context</strong> in very different proportions. A
      meaning that German marks in the verb's inflection, English fixes by position, and Chinese —
      largely isolating — leaves to context, marking tense, number, and even part of speech by the
      surrounding sentence rather than by form. If a model handles all three, is it tracking the
      same underlying meaning, or three different surface cues that happen to correlate with it?
    </p>

    <p>
      What makes this worth pursuing is that <strong>language typology comes with a ground truth
      already attached</strong>. Establishing the structure a model <em>should</em> be using is
      usually the hard part of causal-grounding work. But here it is settled in advance: we know
      Chinese has no tense morphology, that German is verb-second with a discontinuous sentence
      bracket, that a Chinese character is roughly one morpheme while a German compound fragments
      into many subwords. Typology hands over the kind of stipulated structure that the
      <a href="/research/mini-causal-models">MiniCausalLang</a> workbench otherwise has to build
      by hand.
    </p>

    <h2>Candidate probes</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Tense without morphology.</strong> Where is tense represented for Chinese, which has
        no verb inflection — and is it a genuine tense representation, or a shortcut on surface
        markers like 了 or temporal adverbs?
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Tokenization as a confound.</strong> The token is not a cross-linguistically constant
        unit: a Chinese character ≈ a morpheme, while a German morpheme can be split across subwords
        or separated discontinuously. Probing "at a token position" compares different things across
        languages.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Word order as a shortcut diagnostic.</strong> If a model handles German verb-final or
        verb-second structure with the order scrambled and still succeeds, it is leaning on lexical
        cues, not genuine syntax — a falsification test in the spirit of Paper 1.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Category minimal pairs.</strong> Chinese lets the same form be noun or verb with no
        surface change (研究 = research / to research). Holding the form constant and flipping the
        category by context gives a controlled probe for whether the model reads genuine syntactic
        role or a surface cue.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Relation to the rest of the work</h2>
    <p>
      The method is the same toolkit used elsewhere — controls, disaggregation, and causal
      intervention — which is what keeps this from being a descriptive catalogue of cross-lingual
      differences. The link to the
      <a href="/research/sc-certification">grounding question</a> is direct: fluent surface use of a
      structure is not evidence that the structure is load-bearing. It also sits close to questions
      of implicitness and ambiguity in language understanding, where what one language leaves
      implicit is often exactly where misunderstanding begins.
    </p>

    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)]">
      Status: early-stage. Observations are being collected and stress-tested against existing work
      on multilingual interpretability, morphology-aware tokenization, and word-order sensitivity
      before any broader claims.
    </p>
  </article>
